1️⃣ HAVING (Filtering After Grouping)
Simple Idea

HAVING is used to filter grouped data

👉 It answers:
“After grouping, which groups do I want?”

Mental Model 🧠

Think:

WHERE → filter rows BEFORE grouping
HAVING → filter groups AFTER grouping
Example Table
name	branch	marks
Akshay	CSE	85
Neha	CSE	90
Rahul	ECE	72
Rohit	ECE	80
Problem

👉 “Show only branches where average marks > 80”

SQL Query
SELECT branch, AVG(marks)
FROM students
GROUP BY branch
HAVING AVG(marks) > 80;
Output
branch	avg_marks
CSE	87.5
Step-by-Step Understanding
1. GROUP BY branch
2. Calculate AVG for each group
3. HAVING filters those groups
Python Connection 🧠
from collections import defaultdict

groups = defaultdict(list)

for s in students:
    groups[s["branch"]].append(s["marks"])

for branch in groups:
    avg = sum(groups[branch]) / len(groups[branch])
    if avg > 80:
        print(branch, avg)

👉 SQL replaces group + filter logic

Why HAVING is Needed

👉 WHERE cannot be used with aggregate functions

❌ Wrong:

SELECT branch, AVG(marks)
FROM students
WHERE AVG(marks) > 80
GROUP BY branch;

✔ Correct:

HAVING AVG(marks) > 80
Memory Trick 🧠
HAVING = Filter groups
2️⃣ DISTINCT (Removing Duplicates)
Simple Idea

DISTINCT removes duplicate values

👉 It answers:
“Show only unique values”

Example Table
name	branch
Akshay	CSE
Rahul	ECE
Neha	CSE
Rohit	ECE
Without DISTINCT
SELECT branch FROM students;

👉 Output:

CSE
ECE
CSE
ECE
With DISTINCT
SELECT DISTINCT branch FROM students;

👉 Output:

CSE
ECE
Python Connection 🧠
branches = set(s["branch"] for s in students)
print(branches)

👉 SQL DISTINCT ≈ Python set()

Why DISTINCT is Useful

✔ Remove duplicates
✔ Get unique values
✔ Useful in analytics

Combine DISTINCT with COUNT
SELECT COUNT(DISTINCT branch) FROM students;

👉 Count unique branches

Memory Trick 🧠
DISTINCT = Remove duplicates
🔥 Placement Insight

Very common questions:

Q1: Difference between WHERE and HAVING?
